Despite his notoriety, Mr Ashton said everyone at the school was expected to pay tribute to Barrett, who had died young.

'The fact that he was so well regarded by the school despite being a notorious molester made me feel very confused and powerless,' he said.

Mr Ashton said he was nine when he went to Knox and from the start he was abused 'openly and brazenly' by another teacher, Barrie Stewart.

He said the sexual abuse he suffered led him to become a teenage sex worker, according to the ABC. 

